The paper presents new data structures for approximately counting the number of points in orthogonal ranges in one, two, and three dimensions. This falls under the category of computational geometry (cs.CG) and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the use of logarithmic and polynomial time algorithms, which could potentially fall under the categories of discrete mathematics (cs.DM), information theory (cs.IT), and social and information networks (cs.SI).
